reassessment, as the European regional model faces a sovereign debt crisis while Asian economies see more secure sources of growth from their immediate neighbors. Asia's regional institutions display a distinctive combination of decision rules, commitment devices, and membership practices, shaped by underlying features of the region, the dynamics of regional integration, and the availability of institutional substitutes. Within this context, the authors propose changes that will better sustain the prosperity and peace that have marked Asia in recent decades.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aInternational economic integration. 0aRegionalism (International organization) 0aRegionalismzAsia. 4aAsia. 4aEuropean Union. 4aLatin America. 4acourts. 4adelegation. 4aeconomic crisis. 4aeconomic integration. 4amembership. 4aregional institutions. 4asupranational. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aKahler, Miles, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMacIntyre, Andrew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780804789301zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804789301423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804789301.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles